docs.lead_paragraph: Minister WALKER goes to New-York tomorrow, to arrange private business, preparatory to his departure for China, which is now likely to be about the middle of August. It is not determined, yet, how he will go. It has been proposed that Government make a requisition for a mail steamer for Mr. WALKER'S use, but I cannot learn that the project is seriously entertained.

byline.original: Special Dispatch to the New-York Daily Times

docs.lead_paragraph: THE EXILID ARCHBISHOP OF BOGOTA.-We are happy to learn that the illustrious Confessor, Archbishop MOSQUERA, has arrived safely in Paris, along with his brother and friends. His health however, was very poor, although the distinguished medical care that he now receives, and from which we hope much for him, gives encouragement that in a few weeks his case will mend.

headline.main: PHILADELPHIA.; The Rains--Fears of a Freshet--on the Schuylkill--The Fugitive Slave Case again--Important Railroad Cases--A New Trick of the Sharpers--Funeral of John Price Wetherill--The Yellow Fever.

docs.lead_paragraph: During the past two days we have had several very heavy showers, which have done immense good to the crops in the vicinity of the city. This morning a report prevailed that the rains had caused a freshet in the Schuylkill, causing much destruetion of property. It turned out, however, to be untrue.

headline.main: PHILADELPHIA.; The Fugitive Slave Case--The Health of the City, &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: The fugitive slave, BILL FISHER, was up again this morning before the Court of Quarter Sessions, and created considerable excitement. Last night, Marshal WYNKOOP surrendered him to the Court, on the writ of habeas corpus, which was issued on last Thursday or Friday, and he was handed over to the keeper of Moyamensing prison.

docs.lead_paragraph: I consider the Russio-Oriental affair as hopeless. I am far from sharing the Deaceful anticipations entertained by the British and French Cabinets. My grounds for alarm are the following: Prince GORTSCHAKOFF has sent the Russian General NIPPOKONTSCHINSKI to Chumla, on some errand connected with the ultimatum.
